<https://guia-kg.skai.etsisi.upm.es/resource/45000120/2025-26/evaluation> a ns1:EvaluationSystem ;
    ns1:evaluationDescription """The student has two possibilities to pass the subject; a continuum assessment or a final exam.
CONTINUUM ASSESSMENT

The assessment of the subject is ranged from 0 to 10 points according to the following criterion.

Two different mid-term exams. Those exams will consist on practical exercises and theory test-type questions.
Partial exam1: Covers the general theory of the subject. The student will obtain one marks named P1.
Partial exam2: Covers applications of the subject. The final mark for Partial exam2 named P2
The final mark of the exams will be the average:
T=(P1*P2 )/2

Three exercises of simulation of virtual experiments being the corresponding marks S1, S2 and S3.
Those exercises are mandatory. Each exercise has a weigh of 1/3, and the final simulation mark is computed by the artimetic mean:
S=(S1+S2+S3)/3

Finally the weigth of the exams is 80% and simulation exercides 20%.
The final mark for the subject is computed following the following expression:
MM-III=0.2S+0.8T
To pass the subject, a minimum of 5 points is required

FINAL EXAM ASSESSMENT (January)
Covers the whole subject where theory test-type question and practical exercises are to be solved, giving a mark called "Jan"ranging from 0 to 10.
There is just one opportunity at the end of the course (January).
The marks obtained from the continuum assessments are NOT considered here, except of simulation exercises wich are mandatory.
To pass the subject, a minimum of 5 points is required.
MM-III=0.2*S+0.8*Jan

EXTRAORDINARY EXAM ASSESSMENT (July)
Covers the whole subject and only practical exercises are to be solved, giving a mark ranging from 0 to 10.
There just one opportunity at the end of the course (July).
The marks obtained from the continuum assessments and simulation exercises are NOT considered here.
To pass the subject, a minimum of 5 points is required."""@es .

